p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Custody rate<sup>(3)</sup></p></td><td><p>3%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td><td><p>2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(1) The sentence shown is the most severe sentence given for the principal offence (i.e. the principal sentence), secondary sentences given for the principal offence and sentences for non-principal offences are not counted in the tables.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>(3) The proportion of offenders sentenced who are sentenced to immediate custody.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ref: PQ 33331</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-04-18T12:59:28.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510141/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510141/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Sentencing: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of women sentenced in each police force area in Wales were sentenced to immediate custody in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","33331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510142","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The overall investment plans have not been changed following the recent announcements of court closures. No new technology equipment will be installed into courts that are now planned to close.</p><p> </p><p>In regards to the Calderdale local justice area, the HMCTS Reform programme is designed to deliver an improved service nationwide. There is no intention to publish plans specifically for technology investments in the Calderdale Local Justice area.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-18T15:34:53.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510142/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510142/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Courts and Tribunals: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to his Written Statement of 11 February 2016, HCWS540, on HM Courts and Tribunals Service estate, whether his Department's plans for updating the technology of that estate have been revised following that announcement of additional court closures; and if he will publish his plans for technology investments in the Calderdale Local Justice area over the next four years.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","33324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510143","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-19","<p>The five-year £700m modernisation programme of the courts and tribunals, will build a justice system that is swifter and more certain. This programme incurred expenditure of c.£10.2m for the six months to end September 2015.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-19T16:41:56.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510143/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510143/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Courts and Tribunals: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, how much of the £700m fund for updating the technology on the courts and tribunals estate was spent prior to October 2015.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","33325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510144","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>This information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-14T13:44:01.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510144/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510144/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the additional costs incurred by his Department arising from appeal hearings at the First-tier Tribunal (Asylum and Immigration) being adjourned as a result of no Home Office representative being present.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","33377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510146","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>The key performance target under the Language Services contract relates to successful completion of service requests for the provision of interpreters. The contract sets out a 98% target completion rate. The success rates for the first six months of the last financial year 2015/16 are 96.4 percent (Q1) and 97.3 percent (Q2). In addition the rate of complaints over this period was at its lowest level at just over 1 per cent.</p><p>Service credits can be imposed on Capita in line with the terms of the contract when performance falls below the contractual level of 98% success rate. From the beginning of the contract in January 2012 until September 2015 Capita TI has paid Service Credits on 44 occasions.</p><p>We are absolutely committed to further improving performance to ensure a standard of language services that meets the needs of all those who use the service in the justice system.</p><p>The contract has delivered significant improvements so far and we now have a system that is robust, sustainable and able to deliver a quality service at an affordable level. Since we introduced a new interpreting contract in 2012 we have spent £38m less on language service fees.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-14T14:10:05.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510146/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510146/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Interpreters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times Capita Translation and Interpreting has met its key performance target since it has been contracted to provide courtroom interpreting services; and how many fines that company has incurred for missing those targets over that period.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","33365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510147","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-14","<p>Following the inquest into the tragic death of Mr Tharmalingham, a prevention of future deaths report has been sent to Serco by HM Senior Coroner for Inner North London under Regulation 28 of the Coroners (Investigations) Regulations 2013. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) has received a copy of the report. Serco are currently considering the report and will respond in accordance with the Regulations. NOMS manages all contracts with third party providers robustly and will work closely with Serco to ensure that the matters of concern identified by the Coroner are examined and appropriately addressed.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-14T13:58:04.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510147/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510147/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Sivaraj Tharmalingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to investigate the findings of the report by HM Senior Coroner, Mary Hassell on the death of Mr Sivaraj Tharmalingham, that Serco fabricated the number of checks that its staff made on Mr Tharmalingham at Thames Magistrates' Court.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","33366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510148","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>Ensuring ex-offenders have suitable, stable accommodation and employment is vitally important in helping to break the cycle of reoffending.</p><p>In recognition of the importance of suitable accommodation, the ability to source accommodation is one of the measures against which Community Rehabilitation Companies are assessed.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T15:10:14.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510148/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510148/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-11","Offenders: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the potential benefits of supported housing in helping to rehabilitate ex-offenders by providing them with stable accommodation and helping them find work.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","33423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510149","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government's position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p> </p><p>The UK and Ireland are part of the EU Customs Union, which means that there are no customs controls on the border between Ireland and Northern Ireland. Without this, goods being exported across the border could be subject to various forms of customs controls and their liability to duty determined according to complex Rules of Origin.</p><p> </p><p>The absence of cross-border restrictions has both encouraged cooperation and increased trade over the last twenty years. Overall, around 60 per cent of Northern Ireland’s exports go to the EU, with 37 per cent going to Ireland alone. It is the Government’s view that if the UK left the EU these arrangements could be put at risk.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-04-14T09:59:28.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510149/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510149/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-04-11","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the potential economic effect in Northern Ireland of the imposition of border checks between that country and the Republic of Ireland in the event of a UK withdrawal from the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","33381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510150","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We expect the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement will be a mixed agreement covering areas of both EU and Member State competence. In that case, it will be subject to agreement by each EU Member State, the EU Council and the European Parliament. As part of this process the agreement will be laid before Parliament for scrutiny before it is ratified by the UK. We will confirm the procedures for Parliamentary approval when it is presented for signature.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-14T16:32:20.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510150/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510150/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-11","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether Parliamentary authority is required for UK ratification of the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","33442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510151","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>The property compensation scheme proposed by Gatwick Airport Limited consists of two elements, compulsory purchase and a voluntary purchase scheme (‘Home Owner Support Scheme’). Approximately 168 properties will be eligible for compulsory purchase compensation. The number of properties eligible for voluntary purchase will be determined by the promoters published eligibility criteria in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-19T11:06:52.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510151/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510151/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Gatwick Airport: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on the number of households eligible for the property compensation scheme proposed by Gatwick Airport Limited under the current proposal for the expansion of Gatwick Airport.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","33322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510152","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>Heathrow Airport Ltd. and Gatwick Airport Ltd. have published proposals on their respective websites to mitigate the impacts of aviation noise. The Government is continuing to engage with promoters for all three schemes shortlisted by the Airports Commission to develop the best possible packages of mitigation measures, including on noise.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-19T11:56:39.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510152/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510152/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","London Airports: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what operational mitigation measures have been proposed by (a) Heathrow Airport Limited and (b) Gatwick Airport Limited to reduce the effect of aviation noise in the event of expansion of those airports.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","33323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510153","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>We have developed ‘<em>Pathway to Driverless Cars: a Code of Practice for testing’</em> to promote the safe and responsible testing of automated vehicle technology on UK roads. It clearly and simply sets out that testers must obey all relevant road traffic laws and that test vehicles must be roadworthy; a suitably trained driver or operator must be ready, able, and willing to take control if necessary; and appropriate insurance must be in place. Alongside this we are funding research and demonstration projects and working with international regulatory bodies to develop an appropriate framework for the safe sale and use of automated vehicle technology.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-19T12:18:09.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510153/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510153/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Driverless Vehicles: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps will be taken to ensure the safety of driverless cars.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","33261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510154","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>We know that the insurance industry is keen to recognise and reward technologies that will make vehicles safer; the latest safety features, like autonomous emergency braking, can help reduce insurance premiums. As highly automated, and fully automated, vehicle technology should help reduce collisions, we believe this should be reflected in insurance premiums.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-19T12:23:42.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510154/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510154/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Driverless Cars: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the potential effect of the introduction of driverless cars on UK roads on levels of insurance premiums.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","33262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510155","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>The information requested is in the table below.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>TIMEFRAME</p></td><td><p>NUMBERS OF VOLUNTARY RESIGNATIONS</p></td><td><p>% PROPORTION OF OFFICIALS (based on headcount not Full Time Equivalent Data)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2015 - 31/03/2016</p></td><td><p>462</p></td><td><p>3.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2014 - 31/03/2015</p></td><td><p>489</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2013 - 31/03/2014</p></td><td><p>428</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2012 - 31/03/2013</p></td><td><p>378</p></td><td><p>2.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2011 - 31/03/2012</p></td><td><p>421</p></td><td><p>2.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01/04/2010 - 31/03/2011</p></td><td><p>374</p></td><td><p>2.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport data relates to the central department and its agencies during the timeframe indicated, Highways England are therefore excluded from the 15/16 figures.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-19T10:48:44.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510155/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510155/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Department for Transport: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of officials of his Department resigned in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","33296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510156","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>The projected budgets for the next five years for the (a) Cycle City Ambition Grant, (b) Bikeability cycle training, (c) Highways England Funding and (d) Access Funds are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> Programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cycle Cities Ambition grant</p></td><td><p>£99m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bikeability cycle training grant</p></td><td><p>£50m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways England Fund</p></td><td><p>£85m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sustainable Travel Transition Year / Access Fund</p></td><td><p>£80m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Much more widely, however, other Government funding streams will also contribute to projects which will deliver improved cycling and walking. Through the Local Growth Fund, an investment of at least £476m is planned by local enterprise partnerships for cycling infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p>From the Integrated Transport Block funding, local authorities will use £194m to invest in cycling and walking.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding highways maintenance, from 2018/19 the plan is to change the formula used to allocate local highways maintenance capital funding so that it also takes into account footways and cycleways as well as the roads, bridges and street lighting, which it is currently based on. Once implemented, around 9% of the funding for local highways maintenance will be based on footway and cycleway lengths and equates to £196m.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, a record £6bn will be spent on tackling potholes and improving local roads between 2015 and 2021, which will benefit all road users, including cyclists.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-19T12:37:15.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510156/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510156/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Transport: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's current projections are for Government annual spending on the (a) Cycle City Ambition Grant, (b) Bikeability cycle training, (c) Highways England Funding, (d) Access Funds and (e) any other under the cycling and walking strategy programmes for each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","33301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510157","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Pothole Action Fund is worth £250 million over the next five years to local highway authorities in England, outside London. On 7 April the Government announced the share each local highway authority will receive from the £50 million available for 2016/17. Funding is allocated according to the size of the road network the local highway authority is responsible for.</p><p> </p><p>Further details can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cash-for-councils-to-fill-almost-1-million-potholes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cash-for-councils-to-fill-almost-1-million-potholes</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-19T12:27:50.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510157/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510157/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to (a) announce the criteria and (b) begin the bidding process for allocating the funding available through the Pothole Action Fund.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","33299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510158","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>The draft Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy contains two objectives for walking.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-19T12:32:34.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510158/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510158/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Walking: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reason the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy consultation document does not contain measureable targets for walking.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","33300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510159","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) requires larger fossil fuel suppliers to demonstrate that sufficient renewable fuel has been supplied to meet their obligation. The obligation is set as a proportion of a supplier’s overall fuel supply by volume.</p><p> </p><p>Renewable fuels supplied for use in transport in the UK are also reported under the RTFO on a volume basis, in litres or kilograms. The energy content of renewable fuels used in transport is calculated using the default energy values set out in Annex III of the Renewable Energy Directive (Directive 2009/28/EC).</p><p> </p><p>Officials from the Department for Transport and the Department for Energy and Climate Change are in regular contact on the development of proposals to meet EU renewable energy targets, under the Directive.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","33421","2016-04-19T10:09:44.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510159/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510159/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, by what methodology his Department measures the proportion of UK transport using renewable fuels.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","33420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510160","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-19","<p>In February 2016 we confirmed that the Access Fund would be preceded by a £20m Sustainable Travel Transition Year. This competition is live and I therefore cannot confirm how many projects it will support. That said, support for cycling and walking is one of the Fund’s objectives and all bids will need to demonstrate support for cycling and walking in order to secure funding.</p><p> </p><p>The remaining £60m will support the Access Fund, which will launch in summer 2016. I cannot confirm how many projects will be supported by the Access fund, but, similar to the Sustainable Travel Transition Year, I can confirm that support for cycling and walking will be a key funding criterion. We therefore anticipate that all successful projects will support cycling and walking in some way.</p><p> </p><p>The Local Sustainable Transport Fund concluded in March 2016. All 44 projects in 2015/16 supported cycling and walking in some way.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-19T12:41:09.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510160/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510160/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-11","Cycling and Walking: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many cycling and walking projects will be funded annually by the (a) Government's £80 million five-year Access Fund and (b) Local Sustainable Transport Fund.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","33395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510161","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-14","<p>The table below sets out the funding the Department for Transport has allocated to local highway authorities in England (outside London) for local highways maintenance in each year for which records are available. This includes the additional funding the Department for Transport has provided to local highway authorities to help fix potholes and repair local highway infrastructure damaged by severe weather since 2010/11.</p><p> </p><p>Information is not held in the format requested prior to 2010/11 due to changes made in how grant funding is allocated for local highways maintenance. The figures shown are in cash terms and in 2014/15 prices (the latest available). For 2015/16 onwards, the Office for Budgetary Responsibility (OBR) forecasts as at the March 2016 budget have been used.</p><p><strong>£</strong><strong>millions</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2000/01</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2001/02</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2002/03</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2003/04</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2004/05</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Cash Terms</strong></p></td><td><p>264</p></td><td><p>531</p></td><td><p>559</p></td><td><p>566</p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15 prices</strong></p></td><td><p>367</p></td><td><p>729</p></td><td><p>748</p></td><td><p>738</p></td><td><p>822</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Additional Pothole and Other Top Up Cash Terms</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Wet Weather Cash Terms</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005/06</st