"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510320","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-04-20","<p>There have been no redundancies in House of Lords Catering and Retail Services. In June 2015 three sous chefs applied to take Voluntary Exit following a restructuring of back of house services and received a Voluntary Exit package.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-04-20T16:53:03.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510320/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510320/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-04-11","Catering and Retail Services (HL): Redundancy Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees, further to his Written Answer on 9 November 2015 (HL3053), whether the three sous chefs who left via a voluntary exit scheme were offered voluntary redundancy pay.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL7526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510321","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-04-20","<p>The House of Lords is recruiting to fill two Sous Chef vacancies which have recently arisen. These posts have been advertised on the Parliamentary Website, The Caterer and the House of Lords external recruitment portal. No agency has been asked to recruit to these vacancies on our behalf.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-04-20T16:53:21.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510321/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510321/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-04-11","Catering and Retail Services (HL): Employment Agencies","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees how much is the agency fee to engage three new sous chefs, as recently advertised by Berkeley Scott.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL7527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510322","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-20","<p>Defra is not aware of any studies that quantify the extent of garden damage by badgers. Where serious damage is, or is likely to be, caused by badgers or their setts, there is provision within the legislation for action to be taken under licence. Garden damage due to foraging alone is not normally considered sufficiently serious to warrant the issue of a licence.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England receives around 800 licence applications per year to interfere with badger setts. Of these, just over 50% relate to damage caused by badgers but not all involve residential properties or gardens. With regard to gardens, the usual action is to exclude badgers from the sett and proof the area against further damage. There is a presumption against licensing trapping and relocating badgers on disease and animal welfare grounds.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-04-20T11:30:39.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510322/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510322/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-11","Badgers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of damage caused to the gardens of urban and rural householders by badgers in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL7528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510323","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-25","<p>The People’s Trust for Endangered Species’ State of Britain’s Hedgehogs Report 2015 estimated a population of 1.55 million hedgehogs in England, Wales and Scotland in the 1990s. Since 2000, rural populations are thought to have declined by at least a half and urban populations by up to a third. The current population is estimated at around 1 million.</p><p>The reasons for their decline are complex and include a number of factors including intensive agricultural practices (including loss of hedgerows), use of pesticides reducing availability of food, roads, a lack of available shelter in urban areas and restriction of movement and badgers which predate on hedgehogs and compete for their food.</p><p>The Government supports efforts to encourage local communities to work together in supporting the hedgehog such as making our gardens more hedgehog friendly and more welcoming to wildlife in general.</p><p>Working with the British Hedgehog Preservation Society and People’s Trust for Endangered Species the Government has recently published advice for homeowners in the form of five simple steps to make gardens more hedgehog friendly, from letting grassy areas grow wild to providing food and shelter.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-04-25T15:18:29.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510323/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510323/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-11","Hedgehogs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the trend in the size of the hedgehog population in England since 2000; and what is the reason for that trend.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL7529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510324","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The UK has a strong bilateral relationship with Poland, one that the Government is committed to strengthening even further. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), has agreed with his Polish counterpart to work more closely together to enhance the relationship towards a more strategic partnership. The UK and Poland share a vision for the future of the EU and of European security including many foreign, defence and security policy priorities. We are partners in the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO) and share a commitment to the security of our allies and ensuring that NATO continuously adapts to changing threats. We continue to work together to deliver the outcomes of the Wales NATO Summit as we look forward to the Warsaw Summit in July. The UK and Poland are also partners in trade; the UK is Poland’s second largest export market. There are also close historical links between our countries. Together with the President of Poland the Prime Minister was honoured to attend the 75th Anniversary of the Battle of Britain ceremony at St Paul’s Cathedral last September to pay tribute to those who fought, including the brave Polish pilots who played a crucial role in standing up for freedom.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-21T13:50:05.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510324/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510324/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-11","Poland: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the current state of Anglo-Polish relations.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL7530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510325","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>HMRC Overseas Trade Statistics report the value of UK trade in goods with Djibouti. In 2015 the UK exported £11.9 million of goods to Djibouti, in the same year the UK imported £1.4 million of goods from Djibouti.</p><p>Data on the value of trade in services and other types of economic transaction between the UK and Djibouti is not available.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-04-25T12:27:53.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510325/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510325/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-11","Overseas Trade: Djibouti","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the trade and other economic links between the UK and Djibouti.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL7531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510326","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Government is considering the Tribunal’s judgement in this matter, and will respond in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-04-21T14:34:55.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510326/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510326/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","Former Prime Ministers: Allowances","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 3 July 2014 (HL280) about the expenses of former Prime Ministers, and in the light of the ruling of the Freedom of Information Tribunal in the case of Gabriel Webber v Information Commissioner (EA/2015/0194) that the disclosure of details of expenses paid to former Prime Ministers would not breach confidence nor invade privacy, whether they will commit to full transparency regarding former Prime Ministers' allowances including the costs of providing security.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL7532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510327","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Government supports Turkey’s EU accession process, which remains the most effective mechanism for us to support continuing reform in Turkey. However, Turkey’s accession is not on the cards for many years to come. Turkey first applied for associate membership of the European Economic Community in 1959, and there remains a very significant amount of detailed work to do before Turkey is ready to join the EU. The question of whether to hold a referendum would therefore be for the Government of the day, at that time, and for Parliament at that time, when it came to consider the primary legislation which, under the European Union Act 2011, is required before the UK can ratify any new accession.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-21T13:50:44.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510327/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510327/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-11","Turkey: EU Accession","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 21 March (HL6874) about the accession of Turkey to the EU, whether they will now answer the question asked, namely "whether they will hold a referendum in the UK before they agree to the accession of Turkey".","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL7533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510328","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement giving the UK special status in a reformed EU. The Government's position is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. The settlement protects the UK’s rights as a country outside the Eurozone, and makes it clear that the UK is not committed to any future political integration.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-21T15:46:47.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510328/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510328/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-11","UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether it remains their policy to put the UK at the heart of the EU and if so, how this will be achieved outside the Eurozone.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL7534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510329","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-19","<p>Food poverty is the inability of individuals and households to obtain an adequate and nutritious diet, often because they cannot afford healthy food or there is a lack of shops in their area that are easy to reach. There is no single commonly agreed method for accurately measuring the extent of food poverty. Given these challenges we do not think that it would be worth the Department commissioning such research.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-04-19T13:11:20.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510329/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510329/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-11","Food Poverty","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Freud on 22 March (HL6812) about state benefits, why they have not made an assessment of the percentage of food poverty or insecurity that is caused by state benefits being used for purposes other than to provide necessities; and whether they will now carry one out.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL7535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510330","Department of Health","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Government seeks to develop public health policies proportionate to the risks and or harms to health, supporting economic development.</p><p> </p><p>For example, smoking is the biggest preventable cause of ill health and death in England and a significant cause of health inequalities in the United Kingdom. All smoking is addictive and harmful to health. Around half of all regular smokers are eventually killed by a smoking-related illness, accounting for almost 80,000 deaths in England each year. There are significant costs to society in terms of premature illness and death and to the economic prosperity of individuals and communities.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-04-25T13:52:34.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510330/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510330/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-11","Public Health","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the light of the 2016 Institute of Economic Affairs Nanny State Index suggesting that the UK is the third worst country in terms of regulation of lifestyle choices, they will take action to reduce the influence of government on the private lives and lifestyles of the population.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL7536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511487","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-14","<p>Providing the requested information can only be done at the disproportionate cost threshold.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-14T13:26:15.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511487/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511487/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-11","Department for Work and Pensions: Civil Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the public purse has been of legal proceedings against his Department since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","904466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512729","Women and Equalities","false","2016-04-14","<p>Our goal is to deliver educational excellence everywhere, so that every child and young person can achieve to the best of his or her ability. Girls’ key stage 2 results are better than ever and their entries to mathematics and science A levels have increased by more than 12,000 since 2010. We continue to consider what more needs to be done to support equality in educational attainment, in particular the justified concerns about white working class boys.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-14T12:56:54.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512729/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512729/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-04-11","Education: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government plans to take to ensure equality of educational attainment between boys and girls at all key stages.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","904445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512731","Attorney General","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government has a strong record on human rights here and abroad. As examples, it brought forward the Modern Slavery Act seeking to protect some of the most vulnerable and exploited people in our society. It is one of the leading members of the UN Human Rights Council, tackling in particular sexual violence in conflict and we will support £10.6 million worth of human rights projects globally this financial year.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-14T10:22:19.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512731/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512731/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-11","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent steps the Government has taken to promote human rights in the UK and abroad.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","904474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512732","Attorney General","false","2016-04-14","<p>The CPS treats all allegations of hate crime, including those involving disabled people, extremely seriously and continues to place priority on this work. Legal guidance on disability hate crime was refreshed in 2015 and a supporting training package was delivered to all CPS lawyers by January 2016. This equips prosecutors with up to date knowledge to inform their decision making and approach to building the strongest cases possible. In addition, a National Scrutiny Panel on disability is assisting with the development of further refinements to policy guidance on crimes against disabled people and the preparation of a joint CPS/Police/HMCTS statement concerning support to disabled victims of crime.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-04-14T10:34:41.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512732/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512732/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-11","Hate Crime: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps the CPS is taking to improve the conviction rate for hate crimes involving disabled people.","false","Biography information for David Mowat","Warrington South","David Mowat","904471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512733","Attorney General","false","2016-04-14","<p>I meet regularly with Ministerial colleagues to discuss important issues of common interest, including on domestic and international human rights law. I am not able to talk about any legal content of those discussions because, by convention, whether the Law Officers have given advice or not is not disclosed outside Government.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-14T10:24:51.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512733/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512733/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-11","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent discussions he has had with his Cabinet colleagues on the UK's domestic and international human rights obligations.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","904475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506223","Attorney General","false","2016-04-14","<p>The nationality of offenders referred to the court is not collated centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice hold data on foreign nationals held in prisons in England and Wales and publish statistics quarterly. The data does not include those offenders who receive non-custodial sentences.</p><p> </p><p>To obtain even the limited data which is held would require the consideration of the files in all cases over the past three years where the Court of Appeal increased a sentence of imprisonment previously imposed to ascertain if they contained sufficient information for the data to be requested from the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p>The process that would have to be undertaken would incur costs above the current disproportionate cost threshold and would in any event only provide the nationality for a limited number of offenders referred to the court.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-04-14T12:25:58.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506223/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506223/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-08","Offenders: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2016 to Question 31332, if he will estimate the cost of collecting information on the nationality of offenders referred to the court.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","33109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506224","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Government engages with Air Products in relation to their Tees Valley energy-from-waste plant at both Official and Ministerial level. My Department was first made aware of this decision on 4th April and will be working with the Local Enterprise Partnership to explore the impacts of this announcement.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-13T15:56:27.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506224/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506224/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Air Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he was made aware of the decision by Air Products to exit its energy-from-waste business.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","33048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506225","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government has provided a range of support for energy from waste technologies through the Renewables Obligation (RO), the Renewable Incentive (RHI), the Feed-In Tariff and the Contracts for Difference (CfD). The technologies supported include: Landfill Gas, Sewage Gas, Energy from Waste with CHP, Anaerobic Digestion and Advanced Conversion Technologies.</p><p> </p><p>As of the end of 2015, our support has brought forward just over 2.4 GWh of capacity in these technologies, delivering just under 9.4TWh of renewable electricity.</p><p> </p><p>The Green Investment Bank (GIB) has provided support to 20 projects using energy from waste technologies. Direct commitments by the Green Investment Bank (GIB) to date total £334m with additional indirect commitments of £130m to Foresight Group LLP through the Foresight-managed Recycling and Waste LP (RAW) fund, in which GIB is a cornerstone investor, and Greensphere Capital LLP which manages the UK Green and Sustainable Waste and Energy Investment Limited Partnership (UKGSWEI) fund on behalf of the GIB.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-14T13:38:15.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506225/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506225/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506225/answer/previousversion/54962","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-08","Energy: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what support has been provided by the Government for the growth of the energy-from-waste industry.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","33049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506226","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p>The fund to increase the number of degree apprenticeships announced on 24 March 2016 applies to developing degree apprenticeships at both level 6 (bachelor’s) and level 7 (master’s).</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-13T16:27:03.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506226/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506226/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the fund to increase the number of degree apprenticeships that he announced on 24 March 2016 will also apply to masters-level apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","33046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506227","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Where there are redundancies within the Tees Valley, the Government will work with local partners, including the Tees Valley Combined Authority, the Local Enterprise Partnership and the SSI Task Force to determine how support can be most effectively targeted to affected individuals. The SSI Task Force is already supporting the Tees Valley economy more broadly, for example through the £16m Support for Businesses Schemes, which the Task Force reports has created 186 jobs, safeguarded 326 jobs and committed £4.1m funding, attracting £6m in private sector match.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-13T15:58:08.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506227/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506227/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Sahaviriya Steel Industries UK: Redcar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will amend the remit of the taskforce created to respond to the closure of SSI in Redcar to include the Teesside economy as a whole.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","33047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506228","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government’s Impact Assessment for the introduction of the National Living Wage estimates the total cost to businesses at around £1.1 billion, consisting of direct wage costs, associated non-wage labour costs, maintaining pay differentials and transition costs.</p><p>Direct costs to employers contribute just under £700 million to the total cost to raise employees’ wages to the initial rate of £7.20. This will be a direct benefit to employees from receiving higher wages.</p><p>On current OBR forecasts, a full-time National Minimum Wage worker will earn over £4,200 more by 2020 from the National Living Wage in cash terms.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-14T16:26:23.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506228/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506228/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the National Living Wage on (a) costs to businesses and (b) employee pay.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","33120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506229","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills does not hold this information.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-13T16:51:30.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506229/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506229/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Arms Trade: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs attributable to the arms export industry in 2014.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","33220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506230","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) publishes data on the entry rates for full-time undergraduate courses by parliamentary constituency. UCAS does not publish data on the number of entrants by parliamentary constituency, only entry rates.</p><p> </p><p>Latest statistics from the 2015 UCAS End of Cycle Report for the Dartford constituency are provided in the table. The entry rate is given as the proportion of 18 year olds that accepted a place during a UCAS application cycle.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p>Table: Higher Education entry rates for 18 year olds from the Dartford Constituency</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>28.6%</p></td><td><p>23.2%</p></td><td><p>29.9%</p></td><td><p>27.3%</p></td><td><p>32.5%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-13T15:52:13.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506230/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506230/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Higher Education: Dartford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of young people from Dartford who went to university in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","33146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506231","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-13","<p>The Sale of Student Loans Act 2008 prevents Government from treating less favourably borrowers whose loans are sold, compared to the treatment of borrowers whose loans remain on the Government’s books.</p><p>After a sale, the Government continues to finance student loans and collect repayments through HM Revenue and Customs and the Student Loans Company. Purchasers will have no direct relationship with borrowers, and no power to amend the terms of repayment.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-13T11:38:49.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506231/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506231/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he has taken to ensure that the sale of the pre-2012 income contingent repayment student loan book will not affect the amount of debt current graduates owe.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","33156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506232","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-14","<p>HMRC Regional Trade Statistics on the number of firms trading with the EU are publically available through the UKTradeInfo website.</p><p>HM Treasury has published estimates of the number of UK jobs linked to EU exports broken down by region. These are available through the GOV.UK website.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","32610 ; 32611 ; 32612 ; 32613 ; 33159 ; 33160 ; 33161 ; 33163 ; 33164 ; 33165 ; 33166","2016-04-14T15:46:29.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506232/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/506232/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-08","UK Trade with EU: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate the number of (a) UK firms based in London that trade with other EU member states and (b) people employed by those firms.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","33162"
